9541 Plaza Circle
WHEN: Thursday, October 1, 2015  6:00-10:00 p.m.

On October 1, 2015, El Pasoans Fighting Hunger Food Bank will be presenting its inaugural Gala, Wheels Deals Meals, a fundraising event to benefit the Food Bank. The festive evening will feature gaming, a classic and high-end car show, food from 18 of El Paso's finest restaurants, big band, live auction, and cash bars. The event is from 6-10:00 p.m. and is black tie "with a touch of orange" to recognize the color of Hunger Action Month in September.The event is being sponsored by Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Texas, Walmart, Whataburger, Molina Healthcare, Weststar Bank, United Healthcare, 7-Eleven, Laura Rayborn owner of Laura's Productions, and Robert Diaz C.P.A.
Tickets are $50 per person or $500 for a table of 10. To purchase, please call (915) 298-0353 or go online to elpasoansfightinghunger.org.

Throughout a Hyundai Sun Bowl that began looking like an Arizona State rout but ended up as one of the most thrilling games in its 81-year history, one that featured a trade of huge fourth-quarter plays that had the momentum bouncing from sideline to sideline, everything was destined to be decided by one snap.

It came with 45 seconds left, with a resilient Duke team that spent all but 18 seconds scrambling out of hole after hole, sitting third-and-10 on the Sun Devil 14-yard line. Quarterback Anthony Boone spotted star receiver, 5-foot-9 Jamison Crowder, in man coverage against 6-0 Kweishi Brown, streaking toward the end zone, and he lofted a ball toward him that one way or another was going to settle everything.

Read more: http://epti.ms/1x9RpfJ

Duke was on the door step of the end zone for a much needed touchdown that would have possibly led to a win over Arizona State on Saturday in the 81st Hyundai Sun Bowl game at Sun Bowl Stadium.

However, with less than a minute to go in the fourth quarter, Arizona State defensive back Kweishi Brown picked off Duke quarterback Anthony Boone's pass intended for wide receiver Jamison Crowder to put the game away with a 36-31 win for the Sun Devils.

A woman whose body was discovered in a drum filled with acid in Juarez about 20 years ago turned out to be a nightclub dancer from El Paso who was killed by the Carrillo Fuentes drug cartel, according to a retired U.S. federal agent who investigated the cartel in the border region.

The victim, California native Caroline "Tammy" Morrison, may have been killed to keep her from revealing the cartel's link to a stash house in El Paso that the cartel had asked her to lease for them, said Ed Follis, a retired Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) investigator and author of a new book about his undercover work for the agency.

A 23-year-old Central El Paso woman has been arrested in connection with a fatal car crash that killed a man early Saturday morning, police said.

Noemi Juarez, of the 3300 block of Johnson, was arrested and booked into El Paso County jail on suspicion of intoxicated manslaughter after she was released from the hospital.

The crash happened at about 2:30 a.m. Saturday along the 9100 block of Dyer Street.

Juarez was driving a Jeep Cherokee at a high rate of speed southbound on Dyer, police said. At that time, a Chevrolet Cruze, driven by a 21-year-old man who has only been identified as a Fort Bliss resident, entered Dyer from a fast-food restaurant.

SANTA TERESA>> Covering his ears, 4-year old Jaden Armenta urged his father to get him closer to the action at Saturday's Amigo Airsho.

Jaden and his father, Tommie Armenta, were getting ready to catch the last air performance.

"Let's go to the fence," Jaden told his father.

Carrying his son on his shoulders, Tommie Armenta got him closer to the tarmac.

They watched the 45-minute performance from the U.S. Airforce Thunderbirds who drew "oohs" and "aahs" from about 8,000 spectators as highly-skilled pilots performed aerobatic tricks in the sky.

Two Texas political scientists and an El Paso Times analysis of early-voting numbers indicate discouraging results for Democrats hoping to get their voters to the polls to cast early ballots.

In recent cycles, early voting has served as an increasingly good predictor of the final tally on Election Day, which is Tuesday.

The political scientists said it's unlikely that State Sen. Wendy Davis, Democratic candidate for governor, will get within the 10 percentage points of her opponent, Republican Attorney General Greg Abbott.

To get within that margin would mark a moral victory for Democrats hoping to turn Texas blue in the next six to eight years, experts have said.

Read more: http://epti.ms/13tUSKI

MOJAVE, Calif. (AP) - Billionaire Virgin Galactic founder Richard Branson vowed Saturday to find out what caused the crash of his prototype space tourism rocket, killing one crew member and injuring another, but sounded a cautious note about any move to quickly push the project forward.
